 After some feedback though,

6
00:00:12,270 --> 00:00:15,345
 you'll likely want to start formalizing your designs a little bit more.

7
00:00:15,345 --> 00:00:18,015
 One way of doing this would be called wireframing.

8
00:00:18,015 --> 00:00:19,980
 In wireframing, we use

9
00:00:19,980 --> 00:00:23,580
 some more detailed tools to mark up what an interface might look like.

10
00:00:23,580 --> 00:00:28,500
 For example, my paper prototype from earlier might become a wireframe like this.

11
00:00:28,500 --> 00:00:31,890
 This lets us experiment with some additional details like font size,

12
00:00:31,890 --> 00:00:34,860
 colors, and the challenges of screen real estate.

13
00:00:34,860 --> 00:00:37,280
 Now, there are lots of tools out there for wireframing that

14
00:00:37,280 --> 00:00:39,890
 come equipped with built-in common widgets and layouts.

15
00:00:39,890 --> 00:00:44,510
 But you can also do some rudimentary wireframing in something as simple as PowerPoint.

16
00:00:44,510 --> 00:00:47,050
 Google Drawings can be used the same way as well.

17
00:00:47,050 --> 00:00:48,770
 So, you don't need to get super fancy.

18
00:00:48,770 --> 00:00:50,615
 Although if you do a lot of wireframing,

19
00:00:50,615 --> 00:00:53,240
 you're probably want to find a more streamlined tool.

20
00:00:53,240 --> 00:00:58,240
 Some of the more popular paid products include Balsamiq and Axure.

21
00:00:58,240 --> 00:01:00,829
 These are both targeted more at professionals

22
00:01:00,829 --> 00:01:03,410
 working in user interface or user experience design,

23
00:01:03,410 --> 00:01:06,385
 especially on teams and collaborating with a lot of people.

24
00:01:06,385 --> 00:01:10,130
 If you're familiar with the suites of tools from either Microsoft or Adobe,

25
